column6: I thought this was a conference about soap and the soap industry, but it was basically a four-day foam party with a couple of informative sessions.

Whilst there were some burst-out sessions, most of the content was just a bit too airy for me. I thought that the amount of content around bar soap was too low given recent the resurgence in this market attributable to anti-plastic environmental movements.
column7: "You get a bar, you get a bar, you all get a bar!"
column8: "Bar out of hell: return of the bar"

column6: The company lacks lathership, there’s an air of the unclean from management.
column7: The giant sculpture made of soap was a foam favourite of mine. The competition helped gel the community together, no need for pre-conditioning or Prep.

column6: Adequate sudz, but would enjoy more.

I'm going to have to come clean and say it was a total sham, poo in fact. The whole conference turned into quite the soap opera. Getting into sessions was a right pa-lather, and to be honest I need to ex-sponge the whole thing from my memory.

column6: There were suds all over the floor, I slipped at least 6 times over the course of the week and to add insult to injury one time I fell into a bath filled with soap. I was drenched and didn't have a change of clothes! However I did smell fabulous after. 3/10
column8: How I became clean from my soap addiction'

column7: The gift of being able to leave

column6: The talks were good, but there was just too much soap. It was all over the floor. People were slipping and tripping and sliding everywhere. It's been three weeks, and I still smell like an ungodly mix of mango and mint and sea breeze and hibiscus. My skin is raw. I sneeze soap bubbles.
column7: The cakes of soap. Flagrantly mislabelled, I only realised that they weren't actual cakes until after the first few bites, but I never knew soap could be so delicious. Thank you for accidentally introducing me to my new favourite snack. On the go, between meals, or after an evening at the pub, a cake of soap is a low-calorie treat that takes "clean eating" to the next level!
column8: Land of Soap and Glory: not just a bubble market! How the British soap industry's emergent detergents gathered around lather and foxed Big Hydroxide.

column6: Would be great to have more speakers next time
I would frankly lather be anywhere else than here.

column8: The only session that was anywhere close to decent was 'DeterGents: Tackling Gender Inequality In The Soap Industry'
